YAOUND - A Cameroon military tribunal on Monday jailed a Radio France International correspondent for 10 years for his "failure to denounce acts of terrorism."Amnesty International quickly condemned the sentencing of Ahmed Abba.He was further convicted of "laundering the proceeds of terrorist acts" and fined a sum equivalent to about 85,000 euros (R1.9-million).The journalist faces an additional five years in jail if he fails to pay the fine.[WATCH] Chairperson of the African Editors Forum @JovialRantao on #AhmedAbba's death penalty after convicted terrorism charges. #DStv 403 pic.twitter.com/zNSAXwBTd1His defence team said it would appeal.Abba had denied all the charges.READ: Ipid probing Zimbabwean journalist's deathThe prosecution had demanded a life sentence for the reporter, who works for RFI's Hausa language service, and there were initial fears he might even face a death sentence.Authorities believe Abba, who says he was tortured for three months by intelligence agents before being transferred to a jail, collaborated with Boko Haram and failed to pass on information about planned attacks.Amnesty International said the sentence was "a travesty of justice."Ahmed Abba's conviction, after torture and an unfair trial, was clear evidence that Cameroon s military courts were not competent to try civilians and should not", the rights group said.Abba, who had been reporting out of the troubled north of the country, a region repeatedly targeted by Boko Haram, was arrested in July 2015 in the far northern town of Maroua.AFP